# NOTICE

## On attribution

This project — Alter-Me, also called Me-Alter — is not the work of one person.
It is one rendering of a pattern that has been worked on by many people, across
many disciplines, across many centuries, in many languages, through many media.
The framework underlying this project (sometimes called the Spoon Economy)
synthesizes ideas, vocabularies, and observations that belong to a wide
intellectual and cultural commons.

This file exists to credit, as openly and as broadly as possible, the lineages
that fed this work. The list is incomplete by necessity — any honest list
would be — but the principle is total: everyone gets credit for everything.
Always. This is our work as a species.

If you find your own work, your teacher's work, your tradition's work reflected
here without credit, please open an issue or pull request. The list is meant
to grow.

